                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18430130-753-offence-1 t18430130-name-964"></join>John Pearce</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-965" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-965" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-965" type="surname" value="PEARCE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-965" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS PEARCE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live with my father, John Pearce, at Shepherd's Bush; he is a carpenter, and is finishing the house where we are residing; the prisoner is a plasterer, and was employed there by my father—we had some tools, which I put into a box, on the 20th of Jan., which was put into the next room to the one we live in—there were four planes, and the other articles stated in the indictment in it—these are the tools—they are my father's.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I removed them from the kitchen up to that room. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> No, I took them up myself.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-966" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-966" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-966" type="surname" value="HAMPSTEAD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-966" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY HAMPSTEAD</persName>
                  </hi>. I conduct the business of Mr. Aldhouse, a pawn<lb></lb>broker,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184301300171"></xptr>
               <p>at Hammersmith. On the 21st of Jan. this plane and this saw were pawned by the prisoner; on the 25th he pawned a screw-driver and square; on the 26th another plane; he also pawned some more tools, but I did not take them in—they were all pawned in the name of Smith—the duplicates produced by the officer are those I gave the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-967" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-967" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-967" type="surname" value="PAISLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-967" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN PAISLEY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable T</hi> 86.) I took the prisoner last Tuesday—I found on him fifteen duplicates, eight of which refer to this property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner's Defence.</hi> The prosecutor was taken ill on the Thursday, and the day after I packed up all his tools and took them up into an upper bed-room, and they laid there all the following week—I had no work to do that week—I sat up with him two nights, and stopped with him two days; I merely took the tools, as I wanted a shilling or two that week, not intending to rob him—I had the duplicates all carefully in my pocket, to get them out; I did not deny the fact when I was taken; I had commenced work again the day I was taken.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430130-name-968" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-968" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-968" type="surname" value="PEARCE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430130-name-968" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS PEARCE</persName>
                  </hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">re-examined.</hi> I have known him since last June, but have not worked with him—I never knew anything wrong of him—it is true about my father being ill, and that he sat up with him two or three nights.</p>
